The photophysical and optoelectronic properties of the as synthesized R-CDs were investigated by various characterization tools such as UV/Vis, PL, FTIR analyses under different pH conditions. Fig. 2
                        a shows the combined spectra for UV–Vis absorption, PL excitation, and PL emission. The UV–Vis absorption spectrum of the as-synthesized R-CDs dispersed in water at pH 7 ± 0.1 showed characteristic bands at 234 and 287 nm, which could be attributed to the typical π−π* transition of the aromatic sp2 carbogenic core (C=C) and n−π* transition of the surface functional groups (C=O bond), respectively [18,36]. The maximum excitation wavelength (λ

                           ex
                        ) and maximum emission wavelength (λ

                           em
                        ) of the R-CDs at pH 7 ± 0.1 were 350 nm and 458 nm, respectively. As shown in Fig. 2b, detailed emission fluorescence spectra of the R-CDs at different excitation wavelengths were also investigated. Unlike most other CDs, the R-CDs showed nearly excitation-independent behavior when the excitation wavelength was changed from 300 nm to 400 nm, probably because of the homogeneous surface state [39]. The fluorescence stability of the R-CDs with time was investigated in DI water at pH 7 ± 0.1, as depicted in Fig. S2. The as-prepared R-CDs showed excellent fluorescence stability for 6 months, indicating feasibility of use for a longer period.
